Potassium concentration exceeded all mineral elements at 520.45 mg/100g followed by Calcium at 128.68 mg/100g. Relatively high amounts of Magnesium (76.40 mg/100g) and Iron (9.45 mg/100g) were also present in the flowers. Also, Copper, Zinc and Sodium were present but in lower amounts. Our results reveal higher mineral concentration in CCF than reported in other edible flowers (
 Navarro-González et al., 2014; 
 Prata et al., 2017; 
 Rachkeeree et al., 2018). This explains the role played by 
 C. cristata flowers in ethnomedicine for the treatment of various ailments like osteoporosis, leucorrhea, heart diseases, wound healing etc.
